    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The principal not shrinking as fast as you'd like is a common, and frankly, frustrating, experience, and it's almost entirely due to how interest accrues.  When you start paying, the interest is calculated on the *entire* outstanding balance, which is a very large number, much like a massive pile of sticky, unwashed laundry that the smallest of little, squeaky-toy-sized payment attempts can barely shift.  The interest is calculated monthly, usually based on your remaining principal balance multiplied by your interest rate and the time period.\n\nThink of it this way: your monthly payment is split into two parts—one goes to the interest accrued that month, and the rest goes to chipping away at the principal. In the early stages of a loan, because the principal balance is so high, the interest charge for that month is a significant chunk of your total payment. It's like trying to dig a hole in a mountain with a tiny spoon; most of your effort (your payment) is just filling in the tiny bit of dirt that the interest has already piled up on top of the mountain (the principal).\n\nAs you continue making those full payments, the principal balance *does* slowly decrease. Because the",
      "source": "target",
